               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item1">
                     <locus>(fol. 1r-22v)</locus>
                     <author key="person_3268904">Paulinus of Aquileia (Ps.-Augustine)</author>
                     <title key="work_3459">Liber exhortationis siue De salutaribus documentis</title>
                     <incipit>O mi frater si cupias scire</incipit>
                     <explicit>imperium et potestas in secula seculorum. Amen</explicit>
                     <finalRubric>Explicit epistola beati Augustini ad Julianum
                        comitem</finalRubric>
                  </msItem><msItem xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item1a">  <locus>(fol. 22v)</locus> <rubric>De simonia</rubric><note>'Doctor euangelicus tractatu de simonia capitulo primo': short extract from <persName role="aut" key="person_68939042">Wyclif</persName>, <title key="work_7525">De simonia</title> (ed. Wyclif Society, 1898, p. 13 lines 23-29, 'quando enim ... prauitatem diaboli')
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item2">
                     <locus>(fol. 23r-30v)</locus>
                     <title>'Speculum ecclesiae'</title>
                     <incipit>Per Gallum, qui sedet super pinaculum Templi significat predicator,
                        Proprietas enim Galli est lumen futurum precinere et os suum contra ventum vertere. Ita predicator semper os suum contra contrarietates diaboli vertit. Gallus innititur virge feree que inflexibilis est per quam significatur quam recte predicacionem suam debet dicere</incipit>
                     <explicit>Nota quod iudeus dicitur a iuda et non quia omnes iudei ex tribu iude descenderunt, sed quia maior erat inter eos</explicit>
                     <finalRubric>Explicit Speculum ecclesie</finalRubric>
                     
                     <note>There seems to be only a general resemblance to <persName role="aut" key="person_2298">Ps.-Hugh of St.-Victor</persName>
                        <title key="work_4026">Speculum ecclesiae</title> (PL 188.335-380)</note>
                     <!-- Sharpe Identifications: 
                     PL 177. 335–80; H.Weisweiler, Mélanges J. de Ghellinck, 2.
534–70; Bloomfield 1439.
                     -->
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="3" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item3">
                     <locus>(fol. 31r-48v)</locus>
                     <author key="person_315944519">Edmund of Abingdon</author>
                     <title key="work_1447">Speculum ecclesie</title>
                     <rubric>Incipit liber Sancti Edmundi confessoris, qui nuncupatur, Speculum
                        ecclesie</rubric>
                     <explicit defective="true">ultra se ipsam et nitatur respicere</explicit>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>ed. H. P. Forshaw, 1973, sig. O (p. 12), ending imperfect in ch. 29 (p. 105 line 17).</bibl>
                     </listBibl>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="#sermones" n="4" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item4">
                     <locus>(fol. 49r-176v)</locus>
                     <title key="work_11808">Fasciculus morum</title>
                     <incipit>Frater predilecte ac sodalis preelecte, quia Scriptura
                        attestante</incipit>
                     <rubric>Incipit liber qui vocatur Fasciculus morum</rubric>
                     <incipit>Ut enim habetur in regula beati patris Francisci</incipit>
                     <explicit defective="true">quia sepcies cadit justus et ideo ut tociens
                        posset</explicit>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>ed. Siegfried Wenzel, his sig. L1; ending incomplete in part V.xix (p. 518 line 3).</bibl>
                        <bibl>Siegfried Wenzel, <title>Verses in Sermons</title>, p. 14.</bibl>
                     </listBibl>
                     <textLang mainLang="la" otherLangs="enm">Latin and Middle English</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="5" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item5">
                     <locus>(fol. 177r-178v)</locus>
                     <author key="person_2465074">Richard Rolle</author>
                     <title key="work_4286">Emendatio uitae</title>
                     <incipit defective="true">in spirituali canone voce prorumpens</incipit>
                     <finalRubric>Explicit regula vivendi secundum Ricardum heremitam de
                        Hampole</finalRubric>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>Rüdiger Spahl, <title>De emendatione vitæ. Eine kritische Ausgabe …</title> (Göttingen, 2009), ms. 11 (p. 32), fragment of the twelfth chapter (beginning 12.23, p. 226). </bibl><!--<bibl> Nicholas Watson, Emendatio vitae…, Toronto Medieval Latin Texts 21 (Toronto, 1995), 33–68</bibl>-->
                     </listBibl>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="6" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item6">
                     <locus>(fol. 178v-187r)</locus>
                     <author key="person_2465074">Richard Rolle</author>
                     <title key="work_4289">Iudica me deus</title>
                     <incipit>Judica me Deus, etc. A Deo qui scrutatur cor et renes volo
                        judicari</incipit>
                     <finalRubric>Explicit capitulum de judicio Dei</finalRubric>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>John P. Daly, <title>An Edition of the Judica me Deus of Richard Rolle</title>, Elizabethan
                           and Renaissance Studies 92.14 (Salzburg, 1984), sig. M (pp. xxvi, xxxi-iii), transmitting version D of the text (omitting section B2).</bibl>
                     </listBibl>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="7" xml:id="MS_Laud_Misc_111-item8">
                     <locus>(fol. 187r-188v)</locus><!-- extracts -->
                     <title type="desc">Extracts</title>
                    
                    
                  
                     <note>The main items are (1) on temptation (fols. 187r-v), 'Quandocunque tribularis vel temptaris ... solacium a nobis', printed J. Bazire and E. Colledge, <title>Chastisting of God's Children</title> (1957), p. 260, and shown by them (pp. 260-3) to be ultimately derived from the Ancrene Riwle; (2) a passage attributed to Ambrose (fol. 187v); (3) 'Episcopus non debet aliquid accipere a presbiterijs uel clericis' (fol. 187v); (4) 'De obseruatione ieiuniorum' (fol. 188r-v); (5) constitution of Simon Islip, archbishop of Canterbury, 4 non. Jan. 1362/3, for the observance of feast days (fol. 188v) </note>
                  </msItem>


               </msContents>
